Text: ' (February 12, 1809 – April 15, 1865) was the '
Begin Reference: List of Presidents of the United States
k: null
Text: '16th President of the United States'
End Reference: List of Presidents of the United States
Text: ', serving from March 1861 until '
Begin Reference: Assassination of Abraham Lincoln
k: null
Text: 'his assassination in April 1865'
End Reference: Assassination of Abraham Lincoln
Text: '. He successfully led his country through a great constitutional, military and moral crisis – the '
Begin Reference: American Civil War
End Reference: American Civil War
Text: ' – preserving the Union, while ending slavery, and promoting economic and financial modernization. Reared in a poor family on the western frontier, Lincoln was mostly self-educated. He became a country lawyer, a '
Begin Reference: Whig Party (United States)
k: null
Text: 'Whig Party'
End Reference: Whig Party (United States)
Text: ' '
Begin Reference: Illinois House of Representatives
k: null
Text: 'Illinois state legislator'
End Reference: Illinois House of Representatives
Text: ', and a one-term member of the '
Begin Reference: United States House of Representatives
End Reference: United States House of Representatives
Text: ', but failed in two attempts to be elected to the '
Begin Reference: United States Senate
End Reference: United States Senate
Text: ' as a '
Begin Reference: History of the Republican Party (United States)
k: null
Text: 'new Republican Party'
End Reference: History of the Republican Party (United States)
Text: '.

After opposing the expansion of '
Begin Reference: slavery in the United States
End Reference: slavery in the United States
Text: ' in his campaign debates and speeches,'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Goodwin, p. 91; Holzer, p. 232.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln secured the Republican nomination and was '
Begin Reference: United States presidential election, 1860
k: null
Text: 'elected president in 1860'
End Reference: United States presidential election, 1860
Text: '. Before Lincoln took office in March, seven '
Begin Reference: Southern United States
k: null
Text: 'southern slave states'
End Reference: Southern United States
Text: ' declared their '
Begin Reference: Secession in the United States
k: null
Text: 'secession'
End Reference: Secession in the United States
Text: ' and formed the Confederacy. When war began with the Confederate attack on '
Begin Reference: Fort Sumter
End Reference: Fort Sumter
Text: ' on April 12, 1861, Lincoln concentrated on both the military and political dimensions of the war effort, seeking to reunify the nation. He vigorously exercised unprecedented war powers, including the arrest and detention without trial of thousands of suspected secessionists. He prevented British recognition of the '
Begin Reference: Confederate States of America
k: null
Text: 'Confederacy'
End Reference: Confederate States of America
Text: ' by skillfully handling the '
Begin Reference: Trent Affair
k: null
Text: '''Trent'' affair'
End Reference: Trent Affair
Text: ' late in 1861.  His efforts toward the '
Begin Reference: abolitionism
k: null
Text: 'abolition'
End Reference: abolitionism
Text: ' of slavery include issuing his '
Begin Reference: Emancipation Proclamation
End Reference: Emancipation Proclamation
Text: ' in 1863 and encouraging Congress to propose what would become the '
Begin Reference: Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution
k: null
Text: 'Thirteenth Amendment'
End Reference: Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution
Text: ' to the United States Constitution.

Lincoln closely supervised the war effort, especially the selection of top generals, including commanding general '
Begin Reference: Ulysses S. Grant
End Reference: Ulysses S. Grant
Text: '. He brought leaders of various factions of his party into his cabinet and pressured them to cooperate. Under his leadership, the '
Begin Reference: Union (American Civil War)
k: null
Text: 'Union'
End Reference: Union (American Civil War)
Text: ' set up a naval blockade that shut down the South's normal trade, took control of the '
Begin Reference: Border states (American Civil War)
k: null
Text: 'border slave states'
End Reference: Border states (American Civil War)
Text: ' at the start of the war, gained control of communications with gunboats on the southern river systems, and tried repeatedly to capture the Confederate capital at '
Begin Reference: Richmond, Virginia
k: null
Text: 'Richmond'
End Reference: Richmond, Virginia
Text: '. Each time a general failed, Lincoln substituted another until finally Grant succeeded in 1865. An exceptionally astute politician deeply involved with power issues in each state, he reached out to '
Begin Reference: War Democrats
End Reference: War Democrats
Text: ' and managed his own re-election in the '
Begin Reference: United States presidential election, 1864
k: null
Text: '1864 presidential election'
End Reference: United States presidential election, 1864
Text: '.

As the leader of the moderate faction of the Republican party, Lincoln found his policies and personality were "blasted from all sides": '
Begin Reference: Radical Republicans
End Reference: Radical Republicans
Text: ' demanded harsher treatment of the South, War Democrats desired more compromise, '
Begin Reference: Copperheads (politics)
k: null
Text: 'Copperheads'
End Reference: Copperheads (politics)
Text: ' despised him, and irreconcilable secessionists plotted his death.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Tagg, p. xiii.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Politically, Lincoln fought back with patronage, by pitting his opponents against each other, and by appealing to the American people with his powers of oratory.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Randall (1947), pp. 65–87.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' His '
Begin Reference: Gettysburg Address
End Reference: Gettysburg Address
Text: ' of 1863 became the most quoted speech in American history.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Bulla']
Text: 'Bulla (2010), p. 222.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' It was an iconic statement of America's dedication to the principles of nationalism, '
Begin Reference: Republicanism in the United States
k: null
Text: 'republicanism'
End Reference: Republicanism in the United States
Text: ', equal rights, liberty, and democracy. At the close of the war, Lincoln held a moderate view of '
Begin Reference: Reconstruction Era of the United States
k: null
Text: 'Reconstruction'
End Reference: Reconstruction Era of the United States
Text: ', seeking to reunite the nation speedily through a policy of generous reconciliation in the face of lingering and bitter divisiveness. But six days after the surrender of Confederate commanding general '
Begin Reference: Robert E. Lee
End Reference: Robert E. Lee
Text: ', Lincoln was '
Begin Reference: Assassination of Abraham Lincoln
k: null
Text: 'assassinated'
End Reference: Assassination of Abraham Lincoln
Text: ' by Confederate sympathizer '
Begin Reference: John Wilkes Booth
End Reference: John Wilkes Booth
Text: '.  His death was the first assassination of a U.S. president and sent the nation  into '
Begin Reference: Funeral and burial of Abraham Lincoln
k: null
Text: 'mourning'
End Reference: Funeral and burial of Abraham Lincoln
Text: '. Lincoln has been consistently '
Begin Reference: Historical rankings of Presidents of the United States#Scholar survey results
k: null
Text: 'ranked'
End Reference: Historical rankings of Presidents of the United States#Scholar survey results
Text: ' by scholars and the public as one of the three greatest U.S. presidents.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Ranking Our Presidents']
Link: http://history-world.org/pres.pdf '"Ranking Our Presidents"'
Text: '. James Lindgren. November 16, 2000. International World History Project.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'gallup']
Link: http://www.gallup.com/poll/146183/Americans-Say-Reagan-Greatest-President.aspx '"Americans Say Reagan Is the Greatest President"'
Text: '. Gallup Inc. February 28, 2011.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [0] Family and childhood
Text: '
'
Section [1] Early life
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: null
Text: 'Early life and career of Abraham Lincoln'
End Template: Main
Text: '
Abraham Lincoln was born February 12, 1809, the second child of '
Begin Reference: Thomas Lincoln
End Reference: Thomas Lincoln
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: Nancy Lincoln
End Reference: Nancy Lincoln
Text: ' (née Hanks), in a one-room log cabin on the '
Begin Reference: Sinking Spring Farm
End Reference: Sinking Spring Farm
Text: ' in '
Begin Reference: Hardin County, Kentucky
k: null
Text: 'Hardin County'
End Reference: Hardin County, Kentucky
Text: ', Kentucky,'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 20–22.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' (now '
Begin Reference: LaRue County, Kentucky
k: null
Text: 'LaRue County'
End Reference: LaRue County, Kentucky
Text: ').  Lincoln's paternal grandfather and namesake, '
Begin Reference: Abraham Lincoln (captain)
k: null
Text: 'Abraham'
End Reference: Abraham Lincoln (captain)
Text: ', had moved his family from Virginia to '
Begin Reference: Jefferson County, Kentucky
k: null
Text: 'Jefferson County'
End Reference: Jefferson County, Kentucky
Text: ', Kentucky,'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Pessen2425']
Text: 'Pessen, pp. 24–25.'
Close Tag: ref
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'white-12_13']
Text: ' where he was ambushed and killed in an Indian raid in 1786, with his children, including Lincoln's father Thomas, looking on.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'white-12_13']
Text: 'White, pp. 12–13.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '  Thomas was left to make his own way on the frontier.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 21.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '  Lincoln's mother, Nancy, was the daughter of Lucy Hanks, and was born in what is now '
Begin Reference: Mineral County, West Virginia
k: null
Text: 'Mineral County'
End Reference: Mineral County, West Virginia
Text: ', West Virginia, then part of Virginia. Lucy moved with Nancy to Kentucky. Nancy Hanks married Thomas, who became a respected citizen. He bought and sold several farms, including the Sinking Spring Farm. The family attended a '
Begin Reference: Separate Baptists
End Reference: Separate Baptists
Text: ' church, which had high moral standards and opposed alcohol, dancing, and slavery.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 22–24.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Thomas enjoyed considerable status in Kentucky—where he sat on juries, appraised estates, served on country slave patrols, and guarded prisoners. By the time his son Abraham was born, Thomas owned two '
Begin Template: convert
k: null
Text: '600'
k: null
Text: 'acre'
k: null
Text: 'ha'
k: adj
Text: 'on'
End Template: convert
Text: ' farms, several town lots, livestock, and horses. He was among the richest men in the county.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Pessen2425']
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Lamb, p. 189.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' However, in 1816, Thomas lost all of his land in court cases because of faulty '
Begin Reference: title (property)
k: null
Text: 'property titles'
End Reference: title (property)
Text: '.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'sandberg-20']
Text: '

'
Begin Reference: File:Young Lincoln By Charles Keck.JPG
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'left'
k: null
Text: 'The young Lincoln in sculpture at Senn Park, Chicago'
k: alt
Text: 'A statue of young Lincoln sitting on a stump, holding a book open on his lap'
End Reference: File:Young Lincoln By Charles Keck.JPG
Text: '

The family moved north across the Ohio River to free (i.e., non-slave) territory and made a new start in '
Begin Reference: Perry County, Indiana
k: null
Text: 'Perry County'
End Reference: Perry County, Indiana
Text: ', Indiana.  Lincoln later noted that this move was "partly on account of slavery" but mainly due to land title difficulties.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'sandberg-20']
Text: 'Sandburg (1926), p. 20.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In Indiana, when Lincoln was nine, his mother Nancy died of '
Begin Reference: milk sickness
End Reference: milk sickness
Text: ' in 1818.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'donald-1996-p30-33']
Text: '  After the death of Lincoln's mother, his older sister, '
Begin Reference: Sarah Lincoln Grigsby
k: null
Text: 'Sarah'
End Reference: Sarah Lincoln Grigsby
Text: ', took charge of caring for him until their father remarried in 1819; Sarah later died in her 20s while giving birth to a stillborn son.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 20.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Thomas Lincoln's new wife was the widow '
Begin Reference: Sarah Bush Lincoln
k: null
Text: 'Sarah Bush Johnston'
End Reference: Sarah Bush Lincoln
Text: ', the mother of three of her own children. Lincoln became very close to his stepmother, and referred to her as "Mother".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 26–27.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '  As a pre-teen, he did not like the hard labor associated with frontier life. Some in his family, and in the neighborhood, for a time considered him to be lazy.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, pp. 25, 31, 47.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 33.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' As he grew into his teens, he willingly took responsibility for all chores expected of him as one of the boys in the household and became an adept axeman in his work building rail fences. He attained a reputation for brawn and audacity after a very competitive wrestling match to which he was challenged by the renowned leader of a group of ruffians, "the Clary's Grove boys".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 41.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '  Lincoln also agreed with the customary obligation of a son to give his father all earnings from work done outside the home until age 21.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'donald-1996-p30-33']
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 30–33.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In later years, Lincoln occasionally loaned his father money.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 28, 152.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln became increasingly distant from his father, in part because of his father's lack of education.  While young Lincoln's formal elementary education consisted approximately of a year's worth of classes from several itinerant teachers, he was mostly self-educated and was an avid reader.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 38–43; Prokopowicz, pp. 18–19.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In 1830, fearing a milk sickness outbreak along the Ohio River, the Lincoln family moved west, where they settled on public land in '
Begin Reference: Macon County, Illinois
k: null
Text: 'Macon County'
End Reference: Macon County, Illinois
Text: ', Illinois, another free, non-slave state.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 36.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In 1831, Thomas relocated the family to a '
Begin Reference: Lincoln Log Cabin State Historic Site
k: null
Text: 'new homestead'
End Reference: Lincoln Log Cabin State Historic Site
Text: ' in '
Begin Reference: Coles County, Illinois
k: null
Text: 'Coles County'
End Reference: Coles County, Illinois
Text: ', Illinois. It was then that, as an ambitious 22-year-old, Lincoln decided to seek a better life and struck out on his own.  Canoeing down the '
Begin Reference: Sangamon River
End Reference: Sangamon River
Text: ', Lincoln ended up in the village of '
Begin Reference: New Salem, Menard County, Illinois
k: null
Text: 'New Salem'
End Reference: New Salem, Menard County, Illinois
Text: ' in '
Begin Reference: Sangamon County, Illinois
k: null
Text: 'Sangamon County'
End Reference: Sangamon County, Illinois
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Thomas (2008), pp. 23–53; Carwardine (2003), pp. 3–5.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In the spring of 1831, hired by New Salem businessman '
Begin Reference: Denton Offutt
End Reference: Denton Offutt
Text: ' and accompanied by friends, he took goods by '
Begin Reference: flatboat
End Reference: flatboat
Text: ' from New Salem to New Orleans via the Sangamon, Illinois, and Mississippi rivers. After arriving in New Orleans—and witnessing slavery firsthand—he walked back home.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Sandburg (1926), pp. 22–23.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] Marriage and children
Text: '
'
