Text: '

Lincoln's first romantic interest was '
Begin Reference: Ann Rutledge
End Reference: Ann Rutledge
Text: ', whom he met when he first moved to New Salem; by 1835, they were in a relationship but not formally engaged. She died on August 25, most likely of '
Begin Reference: typhoid fever
End Reference: typhoid fever
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 55–58.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In the early 1830s, he met Mary Owens from Kentucky when she was visiting her sister. Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Mary if she returned to New Salem. Mary did return in November 1836, and Lincoln courted her for a time; however, they both had second thoughts about their relationship. On August 16, 1837, Lincoln wrote Mary a letter suggesting he would not blame her if she ended the relationship. She never replied and the courtship was over.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 67–69; Thomas (2008), pp. 56–57, 69–70.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In 1840, Lincoln became engaged to '
Begin Reference: Mary Todd Lincoln
k: null
Text: 'Mary Todd'
End Reference: Mary Todd Lincoln
Text: ', who was from a wealthy slave-holding family in '
Begin Reference: Lexington, Kentucky
k: null
Text: 'Lexington'
End Reference: Lexington, Kentucky
Text: ', Kentucky.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Lamb, p. 43.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' They met in '
Begin Reference: Springfield, Illinois
k: null
Text: 'Springfield'
End Reference: Springfield, Illinois
Text: ', Illinois, in December 1839'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Sandburg4648']
Text: 'Sandburg (1926), pp. 46–48.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' and were engaged the following December.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 86.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '
A wedding set for January 1, 1841, was canceled when the two broke off their engagement at Lincoln's initiative.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Sandburg4648']
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 87.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' They later met again at a party and married on November 4, 1842, in the Springfield mansion of Mary's married sister.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Sandburg (1926), pp. 50–51.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '
While preparing for the nuptials and feeling anxiety again, Lincoln, when asked where he was going, replied, "To hell, I suppose."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 93.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near Lincoln's law office.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 125.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Mary Todd Lincoln worked diligently in their home, assuming full household duties which had previously been performed for her by slaves at her home in Kentucky. She efficiently used the limited income available from her husband's law practice.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 95–96.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' '
Begin Reference: Robert Todd Lincoln
End Reference: Robert Todd Lincoln
Text: ' was born in 1843 and '
Begin Reference: Edward Baker Lincoln
End Reference: Edward Baker Lincoln
Text: ' (Eddie) in 1846. Lincoln "was remarkably fond of children",'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 126.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their children.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Baker, p. 120.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Robert was the only child to live to adulthood. Edward died on February 1, 1850, in Springfield, likely of '
Begin Reference: tuberculosis
End Reference: tuberculosis
Text: '.  '
Begin Reference: William Wallace Lincoln
k: null
Text: '"Willie" Lincoln'
End Reference: William Wallace Lincoln
Text: ' was born on December 21, 1850, and died on February 20, 1862. The Lincolns' fourth son, '
Begin Reference: Tad Lincoln
k: null
Text: 'Thomas "Tad" Lincoln'
End Reference: Tad Lincoln
Text: ', was born on April 4, 1853, and died of heart failure at the age of 18 on July 16, 1871.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, pp. 179–181, 476.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

The deaths of their sons had profound effects on both parents. Later in life, Mary struggled with the stresses of losing her husband and sons, and Robert Lincoln committed her temporarily to a mental health asylum in 1875.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Steers, p. 341.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Abraham Lincoln suffered from "'
Begin Reference: melancholy
End Reference: melancholy
Text: '", a condition which now is referred to as clinical depression.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Atlanticoct2005']
Begin Template: cite web
k: url
Text: 'http://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200510/lincolns-clinical-depression'
k: title
Text: 'Lincoln's Great Depression'
k: first
Text: 'Joshua Wolf'
k: last
Text: 'Shenk'
k: month
Text: 'October'
k: year
Text: '2005'
k: work
Text: 'The Atlantic'
k: publisher
Text: 'The Atlantic Monthly Group'
k: archiveurl
Text: 'http://www.webcitation.org/62a4fProj '
