End Template: cite web
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Lincoln's father-in-law was based in Lexington, Kentucky; he and others of the Todd family were either slave owners or slave traders. Lincoln was close to the Todds, and he and his family occasionally visited the Todd estate in Lexington.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Foner (1995), pp. 440–447.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' He was an affectionate, though often absent, husband and father of four children.

'
Section [0] Early career and militia service
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: null
Text: 'Early life and career of Abraham Lincoln'
k: null
Text: 'Abraham Lincoln in the Black Hawk War'
End Template: Main
Text: '

In 1832, at age 23, Lincoln and a partner bought a small general store on credit in '
Begin Reference: Lincoln's New Salem
k: null
Text: 'New Salem'
End Reference: Lincoln's New Salem
Text: ', Illinois. Although the economy was booming in the region, the business struggled and Lincoln eventually sold his share. That March he began his political career with his first campaign for the '
Begin Reference: Illinois General Assembly
End Reference: Illinois General Assembly
Text: '. He had attained local popularity and could draw crowds as a natural raconteur in New Salem, though he lacked an education, powerful friends, and money, which may be why he lost. He advocated navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Winkle ch 7–8.'
Begin Template: page needed
k: date
Text: 'September 2011'
End Template: page needed
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Begin Reference: File:Abe Lincoln young.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'left'
k: null
Text: '150px'
k: null
Text: 'upright'
k: alt
Text: 'Thin man looking to the right wearing a bow tie.'
k: null
Text: 'A sketch of candidate Abraham Lincoln'
End Reference: File:Abe Lincoln young.jpg
Text: '

Before the election Lincoln served as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the '
Begin Reference: Black Hawk War
End Reference: Black Hawk War
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Winkle, pp. 86–95.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Following his return, Lincoln continued his campaign for the August 6 election for the Illinois General Assembly.  At '
Begin Template: convert
k: null
Text: '6'
k: null
Text: 'ft'
k: null
Text: '4'
k: null
Text: 'in'
k: null
Text: 'cm'
k: null
Text: '0'
End Template: convert
Text: ','
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Sandburg (2002), p. 14'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' he was tall and "strong enough to intimidate any rival". At his first speech, when he saw a supporter in the crowd being attacked, Lincoln grabbed the assailant by his "neck and the seat of his trousers" and threw him.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 46.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln finished eighth out of 13 candidates (the top four were elected), though he received 277 of the 300 votes cast in the New Salem precinct.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Winkle, pp. 114–116.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, all the while reading voraciously. He then decided to become a lawyer and began teaching himself law by reading '
Begin Reference: William Blackstone
k: null
Text: 'Blackstone'
End Reference: William Blackstone
Text: ''s '''
Begin Reference: Commentaries on the Laws of England
End Reference: Commentaries on the Laws of England
Text: ''' and other law books. Of his learning method, Lincoln stated: "I studied with nobody".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 53–55.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '  His second campaign in 1834 was successful. He won election to the state legislature; though he ran as a '
Begin Reference: Whig Party (United States)
k: null
Text: 'Whig'
End Reference: Whig Party (United States)
Text: ', many Democrats favored him over a more powerful Whig opponent.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 59.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '  '
Begin Reference: Admission to the bar in the United States
k: null
Text: 'Admitted to the bar'
End Reference: Admission to the bar in the United States
Text: ' in 1836,'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 64.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' he moved to Springfield, Illinois, and began to practice law under '
Begin Reference: John T. Stuart
End Reference: John T. Stuart
Text: ', Mary Todd's cousin.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, pp. 71, 79, 108.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln became an able and successful lawyer with a reputation as a formidable adversary during cross-examinations and closing arguments. He partnered with '
Begin Reference: Stephen T. Logan
End Reference: Stephen T. Logan
Text: ' from 1841 until 1844, when he began his practice with '
Begin Reference: William Herndon (lawyer)
k: null
Text: 'William Herndon'
End Reference: William Herndon (lawyer)
Text: ', whom Lincoln thought "a studious young man".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1948), p. 17.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' He served four successive terms in the '
Begin Reference: Illinois House of Representatives
End Reference: Illinois House of Representatives
Text: ' as a Whig representative from Sangamon County.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Simon, p. 283.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In the 1835–1836 legislative session, he voted to expand suffrage to white males, whether landowners or not.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Simon, p. 130.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' He was known for his "free soil" stance of opposing both slavery and '
Begin Reference: abolitionism
End Reference: abolitionism
Text: '. He first articulated this in 1837, saying, "Institution of slavery is founded on both injustice and bad policy, but the promulgation of abolition doctrines tends rather to increase than abate its evils."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 134.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' He closely followed '
Begin Reference: Henry Clay
End Reference: Henry Clay
Text: ' in supporting the '
Begin Reference: American Colonization Society
End Reference: American Colonization Society
Text: ' program of making the abolition of slavery practical by helping the freed slaves to settle in '
Begin Reference: Liberia
End Reference: Liberia
Text: ' in Africa.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Foner (2010), pp. 17–19, 67.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '
'
Begin Template: -
End Template: -
Text: '

'
Section [0] Congressman Lincoln
Text: '
From the early 1830s, Lincoln was a steadfast '
Begin Reference: Whig Party (United States)
k: null
Text: 'Whig'
End Reference: Whig Party (United States)
Text: ' and professed to friends in 1861 to be, "an old line Whig, a disciple of Henry Clay".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 222.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The party, including Lincoln, favored economic modernization in banking, protective tariffs to fund '
Begin Reference: internal improvements
End Reference: internal improvements
Text: ' including railroads, and espoused urbanization as well.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Boritt (1994), pp. 137–153.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In 1846, Lincoln was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives, where he served one two-year term.  He was the only Whig in the Illinois delegation, but he showed his party loyalty by participating in almost all votes and making speeches that echoed the party line.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Oates, p. 79.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln, in collaboration with abolitionist Congressman '
Begin Reference: Joshua R. Giddings
End Reference: Joshua R. Giddings
Text: ', wrote a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia with compensation for the owners, enforcement to capture fugitive slaves, and a popular vote on the matter. He abandoned the bill when it failed to garner sufficient Whig supporters.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Harris, p. 54; Foner (2010), p. 57.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' On foreign and military policy, Lincoln spoke out against the '
Begin Reference: Mexican–American War
End Reference: Mexican–American War
Text: ', which he attributed to '
Begin Reference: James K. Polk
k: null
Text: 'President Polk'
End Reference: James K. Polk
Text: ''s desire for "military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Heidler (2006), pp. 181–183.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln also supported the '
Begin Reference: Wilmot Proviso
End Reference: Wilmot Proviso
Text: ', which, if it had been adopted, would have banned slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Holzer, p. 63.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Lincoln emphasized his opposition to Polk by drafting and introducing his '
Begin Reference: Spot Resolutions
End Reference: Spot Resolutions
Text: '. The war had begun with a Mexican slaughter of American soldiers in territory disputed by Mexico and the US; Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had "invaded ''our territory'' and shed the blood of our fellow-citizens on our ''own soil''".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Oates, pp. 79–80.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Basler1pp199—202']
Text: 'Basler (1946), pp. 199–202.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln demanded that Polk show Congress the exact spot on which blood had been shed and prove that the spot was on American soil.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Basler1pp199—202']
Text: ' Congress never enacted the resolution or even debated it, the national papers ignored it, and it resulted in a loss of political support for Lincoln in his district. One Illinois newspaper derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'McGovern, p. 33']
Text: 'McGovern, p. 33.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Basler (1946), p. 202.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'MuellerSchamel']
Begin Template: cite web
k: url
Text: 'http://www.archives.gov/education/lessons/lincoln-resolutions/'
k: title
Text: 'Lincoln's Spot Resolutions'
k: publisher
Text: 'National Archives'
k: archiveurl
Text: 'http://www.webcitation.org/62a5gtE9P
'
k: archivedate
Text: 'October 20, 2011'
k: deadurl
End Template: cite web
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln later regretted some of his statements, especially his attack on the presidential war-making powers.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 128.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Realizing Clay was unlikely to win the presidency, Lincoln, who had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House, supported General '
Begin Reference: Zachary Taylor
End Reference: Zachary Taylor
Text: ' for the Whig nomination in the '
Begin Reference: United States presidential election, 1848
k: null
Text: '1848 presidential election'
End Reference: United States presidential election, 1848
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 124–126.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Taylor won and Lincoln hoped to be appointed Commissioner of the '
Begin Reference: General Land Office
End Reference: General Land Office
Text: ', but that lucrative patronage job went to an Illinois rival, Justin Butterfield, considered by the administration to be a highly skilled lawyer, but in Lincoln's view, an "old fossil".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 140.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The administration offered him the consolation prize of secretary or governor of the '
Begin Reference: Oregon Territory
End Reference: Oregon Territory
Text: '. This distant territory was a Democratic stronghold, and acceptance of the post would have effectively ended his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Harris, pp. 55–57.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [0] Prairie lawyer
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Abelincoln1846.jpeg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'right'
k: null
Text: 'upright'
k: alt
Text: 'Middle aged clean shaven Lincoln from the hips up.'
k: null
Text: 'Lincoln in his late 30s – photo taken by one of Lincoln's law students around 1846'
End Reference: File:Abelincoln1846.jpeg
Text: '

Lincoln returned to practicing law in Springfield, handling "every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 96.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Twice a year for 16 years, 10 weeks at a time, he appeared in county seats in the midstate region when the county courts were in session.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 105–106, 158.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln handled many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly the conflicts arising from the operation of river barges under the many new railroad bridges. As a riverboat man, Lincoln initially favored those interests, but ultimately represented whoever hired him.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 142–143.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' His reputation grew, and he appeared before the '
Begin Reference: Supreme Court of the United States
End Reference: Supreme Court of the United States
Text: ', arguing a case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 156–157.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In 1849, he received '
Begin Reference: Abraham Lincoln's patent
k: null
Text: 'a patent for a flotation device'
End Reference: Abraham Lincoln's patent
Text: ' for the movement of boats in shallow water. The idea was never commercialized, but Lincoln is the only president to hold a patent.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 163.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Begin Template: cite web
k: url
Text: 'http://americanhistory.si.edu/collections/object.cfm?key=35&objkey=19'
k: title
Text: 'Abraham Lincoln's Patent Model: Improvement for Buoying Vessels Over Shoals'
k: publisher
Text: 'Smithsonian Institution'
k: archiveurl
Text: 'http://www.webcitation.org/62a7AMeAa'
k: archivedate
Text: 'October 20, 2011'
k: deadurl
End Template: cite web
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In 1851, he represented '
Begin Reference: Alton Railroad
k: null
Text: 'Alton & Sangamon Railroad'
End Reference: Alton Railroad
Text: ' in a dispute with one of its shareholders, James A. Barret, who had refused to pay the balance on his pledge to buy shares in the railroad on the grounds that the company had changed its original train route.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Donald p. 155']
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 155.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Dirck (2007), p. 92.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln successfully argued that the railroad company was not bound by its original charter in existence at the time of Barret's pledge; the charter was amended in the public interest to provide a newer, superior, and less expensive route, and the corporation retained the right to demand Barret's payment. The decision by the '
Begin Reference: Supreme Court of Illinois
k: null
Text: 'Illinois Supreme Court'
End Reference: Supreme Court of Illinois
Text: ' has been cited by numerous other courts in the nation.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Donald p. 155']
Text: ' Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 175 cases, in 51 as sole counsel, of which 31 were decided in his favor.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Handy, p. 440.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' From 1853 to 1860, another of Lincoln's largest clients was the '
Begin Reference: Illinois Central Railroad
End Reference: Illinois Central Railroad
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 155–156, 196–197.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Lincoln's most notable criminal trial occurred in 1858 when he defended '
Begin Reference: William "Duff" Armstrong
End Reference: William "Duff" Armstrong
Text: ', who was on trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Donald150151']
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 150–151.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by '
Begin Reference: judicial notice
End Reference: judicial notice
Text: ' in order to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness. After an opposing witness testified seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a '
Begin Reference: Farmers' Almanac
End Reference: Farmers' Almanac
Text: ' showing the moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility. Based on this evidence, Armstrong was acquitted.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Donald150151']
Text: ' Lincoln rarely raised objections in the courtroom; but in an 1859 case, where he defended a cousin Peachy Harrison, who was accused of stabbing another to death, Lincoln angrily protested the judge's decision to exclude evidence favorable to his client. Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as was expected, the judge, a Democrat, reversed his ruling, allowing the evidence and acquitting Harrison.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Donald150151']
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Harrison (1935), p. 270.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [0] Republican politics 1854–1860
Text: '
'
Section [1] Slavery and a "House Divided"
Text: '
'
Begin Template: see
k: null
Text: 'Slave and free states '
k: null
Text: 'Abraham Lincoln and slavery'
End Template: see
Text: '
By the 1850s, slavery was still legal in the southern United States, but had been generally outlawed in the northern states, such as Illinois.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Begin Template: cite web
k: title
Text: 'The Peculiar Instution'
k: url
Text: 'http://publications.newberry.org/lincoln/exhibits/show/alwayshatedslavery/peculiarinstitution'
k: publisher
Text: 'Newberry Library and Chicago History Museum'
k: archiveurl
Text: 'http://www.webcitation.org/62dB0ccYV'
k: archivedate
Text: 'October 22, 2011'
k: accessdate
Text: 'January 5, 2012'
End Template: cite web
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln disapproved of slavery, and the spread of slavery to new U.S. territory in the west.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Begin Template: cite web
k: title
Text: 'Lincoln Speaks Out'
k: url
Text: 'http://publications.newberry.org/lincoln/exhibits/show/alwayshatedslavery/speaksout'
k: publisher
Text: 'Newberry Library and Chicago History Museum'
k: archiveurl
Text: 'http://www.webcitation.org/62dBlWFGi'
k: archivedate
Text: 'October 22, 2011'
k: accessdate
Text: 'January 5, 2012'
End Template: cite web
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' He returned to politics to oppose the pro-slavery '
Begin Reference: Kansas–Nebraska Act
End Reference: Kansas–Nebraska Act
Text: ' (1854); this law repealed the slavery-restricting '
Begin Reference: Missouri Compromise
End Reference: Missouri Compromise
Text: ' (1820). Senior Senator '
Begin Reference: Stephen A. Douglas
End Reference: Stephen A. Douglas
Text: ' of Illinois had incorporated '
Begin Reference: Popular sovereignty in the United States#Emergence of the term “popular sovereignty” and its pejorative connotation
k: null
Text: 'popular sovereignty'
End Reference: Popular sovereignty in the United States#Emergence of the term “popular sovereignty” and its pejorative connotation
Text: ' into the Act. Douglas' provision, which Lincoln opposed, specified settlers had the right to determine locally whether to allow slavery in new U.S. territory, rather than have such a decision restricted by the national Congress.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'McGovern, pp. 36–37.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Foner (2010) contrasts the abolitionists and anti-slavery Radical Republicans of the Northeast who saw slavery as a sin, with the conservative Republicans who thought it was bad because it hurt white people and blocked progress. Foner argues that Lincoln was a moderate in the middle, opposing slavery primarily because it violated the '
Begin Reference: Republicanism in the United States
k: null
Text: 'republicanism principles'
End Reference: Republicanism in the United States
Text: ' of the Founding Fathers, especially the equality of all men and democratic self-government as expressed in the Declaration of Independence.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Foner (2010), pp. 84–88.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Begin Reference: Image:DredScott.jpg
k: alt
Text: 'Painting'
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '180px'
k: null
Text: 'Portrait of '
Begin Reference: Dred Scott
End Reference: Dred Scott
Text: '. Lincoln denounced the Supreme Court decision in ''Dred Scott v. Sandford'' as a conspiracy.'
End Reference: Image:DredScott.jpg
Text: '

On October 16, 1854, in his "'
Begin Reference: Abraham Lincoln Peoria speech
k: null
Text: 'Peoria Speech'
End Reference: Abraham Lincoln Peoria speech
Text: '", Lincoln declared his opposition to slavery, which he repeated en route to the presidency.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Thomas (2008), pp. 148–152.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Speaking in his Kentucky accent, with a very powerful voice,'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 199.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' he said the Kansas Act had a "''declared'' indifference, but as I must think, a covert ''real'' zeal for the spread of slavery. I cannot but hate it. I hate it because of the monstrous injustice of slavery itself. I hate it because it deprives our republican example of its just influence in the world..."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Basler (1953), p. 255.'
Begin Template: full
End Template: full
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In late 1854, Lincoln ran as a Whig for the U.S. Senate seat from Illinois. At that time, senators were elected by the state legislature.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Oates, p. 119.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' After leading in the first six rounds of voting in the Illinois assembly, his support began to dwindle, and Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for '
Begin Reference: Lyman Trumbull
End Reference: Lyman Trumbull
Text: ', who defeated opponent '
Begin Reference: Joel Aldrich Matteson
End Reference: Joel Aldrich Matteson
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, pp. 205–208.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The Whigs had been irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act. Lincoln wrote, "I think I am a Whig, but others say there are no Whigs, and that I am an abolitionist, even though I do no more than oppose the ''extension'' of slavery." '
Begin Template: cite quote
k: date
Text: 'March 2012'
End Template: cite quote
Text: ' Drawing on remnants of the old Whig party, and on disenchanted Free Soil, Liberty, and Democratic party members, he was instrumental in forging the shape of the new Republican Party.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'McGovern, pp. 38–39.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' At the '
Begin Reference: 1856 Republican National Convention
End Reference: 1856 Republican National Convention
Text: ', Lincoln placed second in the contest to become the party's candidate for vice president.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 193.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In 1857–58, Douglas broke with President '
Begin Reference: James Buchanan
End Reference: James Buchanan
Text: ', leading to a fight for control of the Democratic Party. Some eastern Republicans even favored the reelection of Douglas for the Senate in 1858, since he had led the opposition to the '
Begin Reference: Lecompton Constitution
End Reference: Lecompton Constitution
Text: ', which would have admitted Kansas as a '
Begin Reference: slave state
End Reference: slave state
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Oates, pp. 138–139.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In March 1857, the Supreme Court issued its decision in '''
Begin Reference: Dred Scott v. Sandford
End Reference: Dred Scott v. Sandford
Text: '''; Chief Justice '
Begin Reference: Roger B. Taney
End Reference: Roger B. Taney
Text: ' opined that blacks were not citizens, and derived no rights from the Constitution. Lincoln denounced the decision, alleging it was the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Zarefsky, pp. 69–110.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln argued, "The authors of the Declaration of Independence never intended 'to say all were equal in color, size, intellect, moral developments, or social capacity', but they 'did consider all men created equal—equal in certain inalienable rights, among which are life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness'."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Jaffa, pp. 299–300.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

After the state Republican party convention nominated him for the U.S. Senate in 1858, Lincoln delivered his '
Begin Reference: Lincoln's House Divided Speech
k: null
Text: 'House Divided Speech'
End Reference: Lincoln's House Divided Speech
Text: ', drawing on '
Begin Template: bible
k: null
Text: 'Mark 3:25'
End Template: bible
Text: ': "A house divided against itself cannot stand. I believe this government cannot endure permanently half slave and half free. I do not expect the Union to be dissolved—I do not expect the house to fall—but I do expect it will cease to be divided. It will become all one thing, or all the other."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 251.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The speech created an evocative image of the danger of disunion caused by the slavery debate, and rallied Republicans across the North.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Harris, p. 98.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The stage was then set for the campaign for statewide election of the Illinois legislature which would, in turn, select Lincoln or Douglas as its U.S. senator.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 209.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] Lincoln–Douglas debates and Cooper Union speech
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Abraham Lincoln by Alexander Helser, 1860-crop.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'left'
k: null
Text: 'upright'
k: null
Text: 'A. Helser photographed Lincoln in 1860.'
k: alt
Text: 'Head shot of older, clean shaven Lincoln'
End Reference: File:Abraham Lincoln by Alexander Helser, 1860-crop.jpg
Text: '

The 1858 senate campaign featured the seven '
Begin Reference: Lincoln–Douglas debates of 1858
End Reference: Lincoln–Douglas debates of 1858
Text: ', the most famous political debates in American history.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'McPherson (1993), p. 182.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The principals stood in stark contrast both physically and politically. Lincoln warned that "'
Begin Reference: The Slave Power
End Reference: The Slave Power
Text: '" was threatening the values of '
Begin Reference: Republicanism in the United States
k: null
Text: 'republicanism'
End Reference: Republicanism in the United States
Text: ', and accused Douglas of distorting the values of the Founding Fathers that '
Begin Reference: all men are created equal
End Reference: all men are created equal
Text: ', while Douglas emphasized his '
Begin Reference: Freeport Doctrine
End Reference: Freeport Doctrine
Text: ', that local settlers were free to choose whether to allow slavery or not, and accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 214–224.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The debates had an atmosphere of a prize fight and drew crowds in the thousands. Lincoln stated Douglas's '
Begin Reference: popular sovereignty
End Reference: popular sovereignty
Text: ' theory was a threat to the nation's morality and that Douglas represented a conspiracy to extend slavery to free states. Douglas said that Lincoln was defying the authority of the U.S. Supreme Court and the ''Dred Scott'' decision.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 223.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas to the Senate. Despite the bitterness of the defeat for Lincoln, his articulation of the issues gave him a national political reputation.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Carwardine (2003), pp. 89–90.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In May 1859, Lincoln purchased the ''Illinois Staats-Anzeiger,'' a German-language newspaper which was consistently supportive; most of the state's 130,000 German Americans voted Democratic but there was Republican support that a German-language paper could mobilize.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 242, 412.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

On February 27, 1860, New York party leaders invited Lincoln to give a '
Begin Reference: Cooper Union speech
k: null
Text: 'speech at Cooper Union'
End Reference: Cooper Union speech
Text: ' to a group of powerful Republicans. Lincoln argued that the Founding Fathers had little use for popular sovereignty and had repeatedly sought to restrict slavery. Lincoln insisted the moral foundation of the Republicans required opposition to slavery, and rejected any "groping for some middle ground between the right and the wrong".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Jaffa, p. 473.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Despite his inelegant appearance—many in the audience thought him awkward and even ugly'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Holzer, pp. 108–111.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '—Lincoln demonstrated an intellectual leadership that brought him into the front ranks of the party and into contention for the Republican presidential nomination. Journalist '
Begin Reference: Noah Brooks
End Reference: Noah Brooks
Text: ' reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Carwardine (2003), p. 97.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Holzer, p. 157.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Historian Donald described the speech as a "superb political move for an unannounced candidate, to appear in one rival's ('
Begin Reference: William H. Seward
End Reference: William H. Seward
Text: ') own state at an event sponsored by the second rival's ('
Begin Reference: Salmon P. Chase
End Reference: Salmon P. Chase
Text: ') loyalists, while not mentioning either by name during its delivery."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 240.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In response to an inquiry about his presidential intentions, Lincoln said, "The taste ''is'' in my mouth a little."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 241.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] 1860 Presidential nomination and campaign
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: null
Text: 'Electoral history of Abraham Lincoln'
k: null
Text: 'United States presidential election, 1860'
End Template: Main
Text: '

'
Begin Reference: File:The Rail Candidate.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: alt
Text: 'Lincoln being carried by two men on a long board.'
k: null
Text: '"The Rail Candidate"—Lincoln's 1860 candidacy is depicted as held up by the slavery issue—a slave on the left and party organization on the right.'
End Reference: File:The Rail Candidate.jpg
Text: '

On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in '
Begin Reference: Decatur, Illinois
k: null
Text: 'Decatur'
End Reference: Decatur, Illinois
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 244.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln's followers organized a campaign team led by David Davis, '
Begin Reference: Norman B. Judd
k: null
Text: 'Norman Judd'
End Reference: Norman B. Judd
Text: ', '
Begin Reference: Leonard Swett
End Reference: Leonard Swett
Text: ', and Jesse DuBois, and Lincoln received his first endorsement to run for the presidency.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Oates, pp. 175–176.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Exploiting the embellished legend of his frontier days with his father, Lincoln's supporters adopted the label of "The Rail Candidate".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 245.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' On May 18, at the '
Begin Reference: 1860 Republican National Convention
k: null
Text: 'Republican National Convention'
End Reference: 1860 Republican National Convention
Text: ' in Chicago, Lincoln's friends promised and manipulated and won the nomination on the third ballot, beating candidates such as William H. Seward and Salmon P. Chase. A former Democrat '
Begin Reference: Hannibal Hamlin
End Reference: Hannibal Hamlin
Text: ' of Maine was nominated for Vice President to balance the ticket. Lincoln's success depended on his reputation as a moderate on the slavery issue, and his strong support for Whiggish programs of internal improvements and the protective tariff.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Luthin, pp. 609–629.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' On the third ballot Pennsylvania put him over the top.  Pennsylvania iron interests were reassured by his support for protective tariffs.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Hofstadter, pp. 50–55.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln's managers had been adroitly focused on this delegation as well as the others, while following Lincoln's strong dictate to "Make no contracts that bind me".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 247–250.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Most Republicans agreed with Lincoln that the North was the aggrieved party, as the Slave Power tightened its grasp on the national government with the ''Dred Scott'' decision and the presidency of James Buchanan.  Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Boritt (1994), pp. 10, 13, 18.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Meanwhile, Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, with '
Begin Reference: Herschel Vespasian Johnson
End Reference: Herschel Vespasian Johnson
Text: ' as the vice-presidential candidate. Delegates from 11 slave states walked out of the '
Begin Reference: 1860 Democratic National Convention
k: null
Text: 'Democratic convention'
End Reference: 1860 Democratic National Convention
Text: ', disagreeing with Douglas's position on popular sovereignty, and ultimately selected '
Begin Reference: John C. Breckinridge
End Reference: John C. Breckinridge
Text: ' as their candidate.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 253.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

As Douglas and the other candidates went through with their campaigns, Lincoln was the only one of them who gave no speeches. Instead, he monitored the campaign closely and relied on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party. The party did the leg work that produced majorities across the North, and produced an abundance of campaign posters, leaflets, and newspaper editorials.  There were thousands of Republican speakers who focused first on the party platform, and second on Lincoln's life story, emphasizing his childhood poverty. The goal was to demonstrate the superior power of "free labor", whereby a common farm boy could work his way to the top by his own efforts.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 254–256.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The Republican Party's production of campaign literature dwarfed the combined opposition; a ''Chicago Tribune'' writer produced a pamphlet that detailed Lincoln's life, and sold 100,000 to 200,000 copies.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 254.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [0] Presidency
Text: '
'
Begin Template: see also
k: null
Text: 'Presidency of Abraham Lincoln'
End Template: see also
Text: '

'
Section [1] 1860 election and secession
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: null
Text: 'United States presidential election, 1860'
k: null
Text: 'Baltimore Plot'
End Template: Main
Text: '
'
Begin Template: multiple image
   
k: align     
Text: 'left
   '
k: direction 
Text: 'horizontal
   '
k: width     
k: footer    
k: width1    
Text: '272
   '
k: image1    
Text: 'ElectoralCollege1860.svg
   '
k: alt1      
Text: 'Map of the U.S. showing Lincoln winning the North-east and West, Breckinridge winning the South, Douglas winning Missouri, and Bell winning Virginia, West Virginia, and Kentucky.
   '
k: caption1  
Text: 'In 1860, northern and western '
Begin Reference: Electoral College (United States)
k: null
Text: 'electoral'
End Reference: Electoral College (United States)
Text: ' votes (shown in red) put Lincoln into the White House.
   '
k: width2    
Text: '148
   '
k: image2    
Text: 'Abraham lincoln inauguration 1861.jpg
   '
k: alt2      
Text: 'A large crowd in front of a large building with many pillars.
   '
k: caption2  
Text: '1861 inaugural at '
Begin Reference: U.S. Capitol Building
k: null
Text: 'Capitol'
End Reference: U.S. Capitol Building
Text: '. The rotunda still under construction
'
End Template: multiple image
   
Text: '
On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected the 16th president of the United States, beating Democrat Stephen A. Douglas, John C. Breckinridge of the Southern Democrats, and '
Begin Reference: John Bell (Tennessee politician)
k: null
Text: 'John Bell'
End Reference: John Bell (Tennessee politician)
Text: ' of the new '
Begin Reference: Constitutional Union Party (United States)
k: null
Text: 'Constitutional Union Party'
End Reference: Constitutional Union Party (United States)
Text: '. He was the first president from the Republican Party. Winning entirely on the strength of his support in the North and West, no ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states, and he won only two of 996 counties in all the Southern states.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Mansch, p. 61.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, Douglas 1,376,957 votes, Breckinridge 849,781 votes, and Bell 588,789 votes. Turnout was 82.2&nbsp;percent, with Lincoln winning the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon. Douglas won Missouri, and split New Jersey with Lincoln.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Harris, p. 243.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Bell won Virginia, Tennessee, and Kentucky, and Breckinridge won the rest of the South.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 350.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Although Lincoln won only a plurality of the popular vote, his victory in the '
Begin Reference: United States Electoral College
k: null
Text: 'electoral college'
End Reference: United States Electoral College
Text: ' was decisive: Lincoln had 180 and his opponents added together had only 123. There were '
Begin Reference: Electoral fusion
k: null
Text: 'fusion tickets'
End Reference: Electoral fusion
Text: ' in which all of Lincoln's opponents combined to support the same slate of Electors in New York, New Jersey, and Rhode Island, but even if the anti-Lincoln vote had been combined in every state, Lincoln still would have won a majority in the Electoral College.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Nevins, ''Ordeal of the Union'' vol 4. p. 312.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

As Lincoln's election became evident, secessionists made clear their intent to leave the Union before he took office the next March.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Edgar, p. 350.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' On December 20, 1860, South Carolina took the lead by adopting an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Donald, p. 267']
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Potter, p. 498.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Six of these states then adopted a constitution and declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the '
Begin Reference: Confederate States of America
End Reference: Confederate States of America
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Donald, p. 267']
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 267.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) listened to, but initially rejected, the secessionist appeal.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 362.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Potter, pp. 520, 569–570.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The Confederacy selected '
Begin Reference: Jefferson Davis
End Reference: Jefferson Davis
Text: ' as its provisional President on February 9, 1861.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'White, p. 369.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

There were attempts at compromise. The '
Begin Reference: Crittenden Compromise
End Reference: Crittenden Compromise
Text: ' would have extended the '
Begin Reference: Missouri Compromise
End Reference: Missouri Compromise
Text: ' line of 1820, dividing the territories into slave and free, contrary to the Republican Party's free-soil platform.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'White360-361']
Text: 'White, pp. 360–361.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln rejected the idea, saying, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 268.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln, however, did support the '
Begin Reference: Corwin Amendment
End Reference: Corwin Amendment
Text: ' to the Constitution, which had passed in Congress and protected slavery in those states where it already existed.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Vorenberg, p. 22.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' A few weeks before the war, he went so far as to pen a letter to every governor asking for their support in ratifying the Corwin Amendment as a means to avoid secession.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Lupton, p. 34.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

En route to his inauguration by train, Lincoln addressed crowds and legislatures across the North.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 273–277.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The president-elect then '
Begin Reference: Baltimore Plot
k: null
Text: 'evaded possible assassins'
End Reference: Baltimore Plot
Text: ' in Baltimore, who were uncovered by Lincoln's head of security, '
Begin Reference: Allan Pinkerton
End Reference: Allan Pinkerton
Text: '. On February 23, 1861, he arrived in disguise in Washington, D.C., which was placed under substantial military guard.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 277–279.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln directed his '
Begin Reference: Lincoln's first inaugural address
k: null
Text: 'inaugural address'
End Reference: Lincoln's first inaugural address
Text: ' to the South, proclaiming once again that he had no intention, or inclination, to abolish slavery in the Southern states:
'
Begin Template: quote
k: null
Text: 'Apprehension seems to exist among the people of the Southern States that by the accession of a Republican Administration their property and their peace and personal security are to be endangered. There has never been any reasonable cause for such apprehension. Indeed, the most ample evidence to the contrary has all the while existed and been open to their inspection. It is found in nearly all the published speeches of him who now addresses you. I do but quote from one of those speeches when I declare that "I have no purpose, directly or indirectly, to interfere with the institution of slavery in the States where it exists. I believe I have no lawful right to do so, and I have no inclination to do so."'
Begin Reference: Lincoln's first inaugural address
k: null
Text: 'First inaugural address'
End Reference: Lincoln's first inaugural address
k: null
Text: ', 4 March 1861'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Sandburg (2002), p. 212.'
Close Tag: ref
End Template: quote
Text: '
The President ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends. We must not be enemies ... The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battlefield, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone, all over this broad land, will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched, as surely they will be, by the better angels of our nature."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 283–284.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The failure of the '
Begin Reference: Peace Conference of 1861
End Reference: Peace Conference of 1861
Text: ' signaled that legislative compromise was implausible. By March 1861, no leaders of the insurrection had proposed rejoining the Union on any terms. Meanwhile, Lincoln and nearly every Republican leader agreed that the dismantling of the Union could not be tolerated.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 268, 279.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] War begins
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: null
Text: 'American Civil War'
End Template: Main
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:Major Robert Anderson.jpg
k: alt
Text: 'portrait'
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '170px'
k: null
Text: 'Major Anderson, Ft. Sumter commander'
End Reference: File:Major Robert Anderson.jpg
Text: '
The commander of Fort Sumter, South Carolina, '
Begin Reference: Robert Anderson (Civil War)
k: null
Text: 'Major Robert Anderson'
End Reference: Robert Anderson (Civil War)
Text: ' sent a request for provisions to Washington, and the execution of Lincoln's order to meet that request was seen by the secessionists as an act of war.  On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at '
Begin Reference: Battle of Fort Sumter
k: null
Text: 'Fort Sumter'
End Reference: Battle of Fort Sumter
Text: ', forcing them to surrender, and began the war.  Historian '
Begin Reference: Allan Nevins
End Reference: Allan Nevins
Text: ' argued that the newly inaugurated Lincoln made three miscalculations: underestimating the gravity of the crisis, exaggerating the strength of Unionist sentiment in the South, and not realizing the Southern Unionists were insisting there be no invasion.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Allan Nevins, Ordeal of the Union'' (1959) vol 5 p 29'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '  '
Begin Reference: William Tecumseh Sherman
End Reference: William Tecumseh Sherman
Text: ' talked to Lincoln during inauguration week and was "sadly disappointed" at his failure to realize that "the country was sleeping on a volcano" and that the South was preparing for war.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Sherman, pp. 185–186.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Donald concludes that, "His repeated efforts to avoid collision in the months between inauguration and the firing on Ft. Sumter showed he adhered to his vow not to be the first to shed fraternal blood. But he also vowed not to surrender the forts. The only resolution of these contradictory positions was for the confederates to fire the first shot; they did just that."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 293.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

On April 15, Lincoln called on all the states to send detachments totaling 75,000 troops to recapture forts, protect Washington, and "preserve the Union", which, in his view, still existed intact despite the actions of the seceding states. This call forced the states to choose sides. Virginia declared its secession and was rewarded with the Confederate capital, despite the exposed position of '
Begin Reference: Richmond, Virginia
k: null
Text: 'Richmond'
End Reference: Richmond, Virginia
Text: ' so close to Union lines. North Carolina, Tennessee, and Arkansas also voted for secession over the next two months. Secession sentiment was strong in Missouri and Maryland, but did not prevail; Kentucky tried to be neutral.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Oates, p. 226']
Text: 'Oates, p. 226.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Troops headed south towards Washington to protect the capital in response to Lincoln's call. On April 19, secessionist mobs in Baltimore that controlled the rail links '
Begin Reference: Baltimore riot of 1861
k: null
Text: 'attacked Union troops'
End Reference: Baltimore riot of 1861
Text: ' traveling to the capital. '
Begin Reference: George William Brown
End Reference: George William Brown
Text: ', the Mayor of Baltimore, and other suspect Maryland politicians were arrested and imprisoned, without a warrant, as Lincoln suspended the writ of '''
Begin Reference: Habeas corpus in the United States#Suspension during the Civil War
k: null
Text: 'habeas corpus'
End Reference: Habeas corpus in the United States#Suspension during the Civil War
Text: '''.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Heidler (2000), p. 174.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' '
Begin Reference: John Merryman
End Reference: John Merryman
Text: ', a leader in the secessionist group in Maryland, petitioned Chief Justice '
Begin Reference: Roger B. Taney
End Reference: Roger B. Taney
Text: ' to issue a writ of habeas corpus, saying holding Merryman without a hearing was unlawful. Taney issued the writ, thereby ordering Merryman's release, but Lincoln ignored it.  Then and throughout the war, Lincoln came under heavy, often vituperative attack from antiwar Democrats, called '
Begin Reference: Copperheads
End Reference: Copperheads
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Scott, pp. 326–341.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] Assuming command for the Union in the war
Text: '

After the fall of '
Begin Reference: Battle of Fort Sumter
k: null
Text: 'Fort Sumter'
End Reference: Battle of Fort Sumter
Text: ', Lincoln realized the importance of taking immediate executive control of the war and making an overall strategy to put down the rebellion.  Lincoln encountered an unprecedented political and military crisis, and he responded as '
Begin Reference: commander-in-chief
End Reference: commander-in-chief
Text: ', using unprecedented powers. He expanded his war powers, and imposed a blockade on all the Confederate shipping ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, and after suspending ''habeas corpus'', arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers. Lincoln was supported by Congress and the northern public for these actions. In addition, Lincoln had to contend with reinforcing strong Union sympathies in the border slave states and keeping the war from becoming an international conflict.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 303–304; Carwardine (2003), pp. 163–164.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Begin Reference: File:RunningtheMachine-LincAdmin.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: 'left'
k: null
Text: '300px'
k: alt
Text: 'A group of men sitting at a table as another man creates money on a wooden machine.'
k: null
Text: '"Running the 'Machine'&nbsp;": An 1864 political cartoon takes a swing at Lincoln's administration—featuring William Fessenden, Edwin Stanton, William Seward, Gideon Welles, Lincoln and others.'
End Reference: File:RunningtheMachine-LincAdmin.jpg
Text: '

The war effort was the source of continued disparagement of Lincoln, and dominated his time and attention. From the start, it was clear that bipartisan support would be essential to success in the war effort, and any manner of compromise alienated factions on both sides of the aisle, such as the appointment of Republicans and Democrats to command positions in the Union Army. Copperheads criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on the slavery issue. Conversely, the Radical Republicans criticized him for moving too slowly in abolishing slavery.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 315, 331–333, 338–339, 417.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the '
Begin Reference: Confiscation Act of 1861
k: null
Text: 'Confiscation Act'
End Reference: Confiscation Act of 1861
Text: ' that authorized judiciary proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederate war effort. In practice the law had little effect, but it did signal political support for abolishing slavery in the Confederacy'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 314; Carwardine (2003), p. 178.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In late August 1861, General '
Begin Reference: John C. Frémont
End Reference: John C. Frémont
Text: ', the 1856 Republican presidential nominee, issued, without consulting Washington, a proclamation of martial law in Missouri. He declared that any citizen found bearing arms could be court-martialed and shot, and that slaves of persons aiding the rebellion would be freed. Frémont was already under a cloud with charges of negligence in his command of the '
Begin Reference: Department of the West
End Reference: Department of the West
Text: ' compounded with allegations of fraud and corruption. Lincoln overruled Frémont's proclamation. Lincoln believed that Fremont's emancipation was political; neither militarily necessary nor legal.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 314–317.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Union enlistments from Maryland, Kentucky, and Missouri increased by over 40,000 troops.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Carwardine (2003), p. 181.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

The '
Begin Reference: Trent Affair
End Reference: Trent Affair
Text: ' of late 1861 threatened war with Great Britain. The U.S. Navy illegally intercepted a British merchant ship the ''Trent'' on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys; Britain protested vehemently while the U.S. cheered. Lincoln resolved the issue by releasing the two men and war was successfully averted with Britain.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'CFAdams']
Text: 'Adams, pp. 540–562.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '  Lincoln's foreign policy approach had been initially hands off, due to his inexperience; he left most diplomacy appointments and other foreign policy matters to his Secretary of State, William Seward. Seward's initial reaction to the ''Trent'' affair, however, was too bellicose, so Lincoln also turned to Senator '
Begin Reference: Charles Sumner
End Reference: Charles Sumner
Text: ', the chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee and an expert in British diplomacy.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 322.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

To learn technical military terms, Lincoln borrowed and studied '
Begin Reference: Henry Halleck
End Reference: Henry Halleck
Text: ''s book, ''Elements of Military Art and Science'' from the Library of Congress.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Prokopowicz, p. 127.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln painstakingly monitored the telegraphic reports coming in to the War Department in Washington, D.C. He kept close tabs on all phases of the military effort, consulted with governors, and selected generals based on their past success (as well as their state and party). In January 1862, after many complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced '
Begin Reference: Simon Cameron
End Reference: Simon Cameron
Text: ' with '
Begin Reference: Edwin Stanton
End Reference: Edwin Stanton
Text: ' as War Secretary. Stanton was one of many conservative Democrats (he supported Breckenridge in the 1860 election) who became anti-slavery Republicans under Lincoln's leadership.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Benjamin P. Thomas and Harold M. Hyman, ''Stanton, the Life and Times of Lincoln's Secretary of War'' (Knopf, 1962)'
Begin Template: Page needed
k: date
Text: 'October 2011'
End Template: Page needed
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' In terms of war strategy, Lincoln articulated two priorities: to ensure that Washington was well-defended, and to conduct an aggressive war effort that would satisfy the demand in the North for prompt, decisive victory; major Northern newspaper editors expected victory within 90 days.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 295–296.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Twice a week, Lincoln would meet with his cabinet in the afternoon, and occasionally Mary Lincoln would force him to take a carriage ride because she was concerned he was working too hard.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 391–392.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln learned from his chief of staff General '
Begin Reference: Henry Wager Halleck
k: null
Text: 'Henry Halleck'
End Reference: Henry Wager Halleck
Text: ', a student of the European strategist '
Begin Reference: Antoine-Henri Jomini
k: null
Text: 'Jomini'
End Reference: Antoine-Henri Jomini
Text: ', of the critical need to control strategic points, such as the Mississippi River;'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Ambrose, pp. 7, 66, 159.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' he also knew well the importance of Vicksburg and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than simply capturing territory.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 432–436.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] General McClellan
Text: '
After the Union defeat at the '
Begin Reference: First Battle of Bull Run
End Reference: First Battle of Bull Run
Text: ' and the retirement of the aged '
Begin Reference: Winfield Scott
End Reference: Winfield Scott
Text: ' in late 1861, Lincoln appointed Major General '
Begin Reference: George B. McClellan
End Reference: George B. McClellan
Text: ' general-in-chief of all the Union armies.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 318–319.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' McClellan, a young West Point graduate, railroad executive, and Pennsylvania Democrat, took several months to plan and attempt his Peninsula Campaign, longer than Lincoln wanted. The campaign's objective was to capture Richmond by moving the Army of the Potomac by boat to the peninsula and then overland to the Confederate capital. McClellan's repeated delays frustrated Lincoln and Congress, as did his position that no troops were needed to defend Washington. Lincoln insisted on holding some of McClellan's troops in defense of the capital; McClellan, who consistently overestimated the strength of Confederate troops, blamed this decision for the ultimate failure of the Peninsula Campaign.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 349–352.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Begin Reference: File:Lincoln and McClellan 1862-10-03.jpg
k: alt
Text: 'Photograph of Lincoln and McClellan sitting at a table in a field tent'
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '275px'
k: null
Text: 'Lincoln and McClellan after the Battle of Antietam'
End Reference: File:Lincoln and McClellan 1862-10-03.jpg
Text: '

Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief and appointed '
Begin Reference: Henry Wager Halleck
End Reference: Henry Wager Halleck
Text: ' in March 1862, after McClellan's "Harrison's Landing Letter", in which he offered unsolicited political advice to Lincoln urging caution in the war effort.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 360–361.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' McClellan's letter incensed Radical Republicans, who successfully pressured Lincoln to appoint '
Begin Reference: John Pope (military officer)
k: null
Text: 'John Pope'
End Reference: John Pope (military officer)
Text: ', a Republican, as head of the new '
Begin Reference: Army of Virginia
End Reference: Army of Virginia
Text: '. Pope complied with Lincoln's strategic desire to move toward Richmond from the north, thus protecting the capital from attack. However, lacking requested reinforcements from McClellan, now commanding the Army of the Potomac, Pope was soundly defeated at the '
Begin Reference: Second Battle of Bull Run
End Reference: Second Battle of Bull Run
Text: ' in the summer of 1862, forcing the Army of the Potomac to defend Washington for a second time.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Nevins (1960), pp. 2:159–162.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The war also expanded with naval operations in 1862 when the CSS ''Virginia'', formerly the USS ''Merrimack'', damaged or destroyed three Union vessels in Norfolk, Virginia, before being engaged and damaged by the USS ''Monitor''. Lincoln closely reviewed the dispatches and interrogated naval officers during their clash in the '
Begin Reference: Battle of Hampton Roads
End Reference: Battle of Hampton Roads
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 339–340.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln was desperate, and restored him to command of all forces around Washington, to the dismay of all in his cabinet but Seward.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Goodwin, pp. 478–479.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Two days after McClellan's return to command, General '
Begin Reference: Robert E. Lee
End Reference: Robert E. Lee
Text: ''s forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the '
Begin Reference: Battle of Antietam
End Reference: Battle of Antietam
Text: ' in September 1862.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Goodwin, pp. 478–480.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The ensuing Union victory was among the bloodiest in American history, but it enabled Lincoln to announce that he would issue an Emancipation Proclamation in January.  Having composed the Proclamation some time earlier, Lincoln had waited for a military victory to publish it to avoid it being perceived as the product of desperation.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Goodwin, p. 481.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' McClellan then resisted the President's demand that he pursue Lee's retreating and exposed army, while his counterpart General '
Begin Reference: Don Carlos Buell
End Reference: Don Carlos Buell
Text: ' likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee. As a result, Lincoln replaced Buell with '
Begin Reference: William Rosecrans
End Reference: William Rosecrans
Text: '; and, after the 1862 midterm elections, he replaced McClellan with Republican '
Begin Reference: Ambrose Burnside
End Reference: Ambrose Burnside
Text: '. Both of these replacements were political moderates and prospectively more supportive of the Commander-in-Chief.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 389–390.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Burnside, against the advice of the president, prematurely launched an offensive across the '
Begin Reference: Rappahannock River
End Reference: Rappahannock River
Text: ' and was stunningly defeated by Lee at '
Begin Reference: Battle of Fredericksburg
k: null
Text: 'Fredericksburg'
End Reference: Battle of Fredericksburg
Text: ' in December. Not only had Burnside been defeated on the battlefield, but his soldiers were disgruntled and undisciplined. Desertions during 1863 were in the thousands and they increased after Fredericksburg.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 429–431.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln brought in '
Begin Reference: Joseph Hooker
End Reference: Joseph Hooker
Text: ', despite his record of loose talk about the need for a military dictatorship.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Nevins 6:433-44'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

The '
Begin Reference: United States House of Representatives elections, 1862
k: null
Text: 'mid-term elections'
End Reference: United States House of Representatives elections, 1862
Text: ' in 1862 brought the Republicans severe losses due to sharp disfavor with the administration over its failure to deliver a speedy end to the war, as well as rising inflation, new high taxes, rumors of corruption, the suspension of habeas corpus, '
Begin Reference: Conscription
k: null
Text: 'the military draft law'
End Reference: Conscription
Text: ', and fears that freed slaves would undermine the labor market. The Emancipation Proclamation announced in September gained votes for the Republicans in the rural areas of New England and the upper Midwest, but it lost votes in the cities and the lower Midwest. While Republicans were discouraged, Democrats were energized and did especially well in Pennsylvania, Ohio, Indiana, and New York. The Republicans did maintain their majorities in Congress and in the major states, except New York. The Cincinnati ''Gazette'' contended that the voters were "depressed by the interminable nature of this war, as so far conducted, and by the rapid exhaustion of the national resources without progress".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Nevins vol 6 pp. 318–322, quote on p. 322.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

In the spring of 1863, Lincoln was optimistic about upcoming campaigns to the point of thinking the end of the war could be near if a string of victories could be put together; these plans included Hooker's attack on Lee north of Richmond, Rosecrans' on Chattanooga, Grant's on Vicksburg, and a naval assault on Charleston.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 422–423.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Hooker was routed by Lee at the '
Begin Reference: Battle of Chancellorsville
End Reference: Battle of Chancellorsville
Text: ' in May,'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Nevins 6:432–450.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' but continued to command his troops for some weeks. He ignored Lincoln's order to divide his troops, and possibly force Lee to do the same in Harper's Ferry, and tendered his resignation, which Lincoln accepted. He was replaced by '
Begin Reference: George Meade
End Reference: George Meade
Text: ', who followed Lee into Pennsylvania for the '
Begin Reference: Gettysburg Campaign
End Reference: Gettysburg Campaign
Text: ', which was a victory for the Union, though Lee's army avoided capture. At the same time, after initial setbacks, Grant laid siege to Vicksburg and the Union navy attained some success in Charleston harbor.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 444–447.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '
After the Battle of Gettysburg, Lincoln clearly understood that his military decisions would be more effectively carried out by conveying his orders through his War Secretary or his general-in-chief on to his generals, who resented his civilian interference with their own plans. Even so, he often continued to give detailed directions to his generals as Commander in Chief.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 446.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] Emancipation Proclamation
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: null
Text: 'Abraham Lincoln and slavery'
k: null
Text: 'Emancipation Proclamation'
End Template: Main
Text: '

'
Begin Reference: File:Emancipation proclamation.jpg
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '300px'
k: null
Text: 'left'
k: null
Text: 'Lincoln presents the first draft of the Emancipation Proclamation to his cabinet. Painted by '
Begin Reference: Francis Bicknell Carpenter
End Reference: Francis Bicknell Carpenter
Text: ' in 1864'
k: alt
Text: 'A dark-haired, bearded, middle-aged man holding documents is seated among seven other men.'
End Reference: File:Emancipation proclamation.jpg
Text: '
Lincoln understood that the Federal government's power to end slavery was limited by the Constitution, which before 1865, committed the issue to individual states. He argued before and during his election that the eventual extinction of slavery would result from preventing its expansion into new U.S. territory. At the beginning of the war, he also sought to persuade the states to accept '
Begin Reference: compensated emancipation
End Reference: compensated emancipation
Text: ' in return for their prohibition of slavery (an offer that took effect only in Washington, D.C., in April 1862). Lincoln believed that curtailing slavery in these ways would economically expunge it, as envisioned by the '
Begin Reference: Founding Fathers of the United States
k: null
Text: 'Founding Fathers'
End Reference: Founding Fathers of the United States
Text: ', under the constitution.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Mackubin']
Begin Template: cite web
k: url
Text: 'http://www.nationalreview.com/books/owens200403251139.asp'
k: title
Text: 'The Liberator'
k: first
Text: 'Thomas Owens'
k: last
Text: 'Mackubin'
k: date
Text: 'March 25, 2004'
k: work
Text: 'National Review'
k: publisher
Text: 'National Review'
k: archiveurl
Text: 'http://www.webcitation.org/62a7fJ9hj'
k: archivedate
Text: 'October 20, 2011'
k: deadurl
End Template: cite web
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' President Lincoln rejected two geographically limited emancipation attempts by Major General '
Begin Reference: John C. Frémont
End Reference: John C. Frémont
Text: ' in August 1861 and by Major General '
Begin Reference: David Hunter
End Reference: David Hunter
Text: ' in May 1862, on the grounds that it was not within their power, and it would upset the border states loyal to the Union.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Guelzo (1999), pp. 290–291.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

On June 19, 1862, endorsed by Lincoln, Congress passed an act banning slavery on all federal territory. In July 1862, the Second '
Begin Reference: Confiscation Acts
k: null
Text: 'Confiscation Act'
End Reference: Confiscation Acts
Text: ' was passed, which set up court procedures that could free the slaves of anyone convicted of aiding the rebellion. Although Lincoln believed it was not within Congress's power to free the slaves within the states, he approved the bill in deference to the legislature. He felt such action could only be taken by the commander-in-chief using war powers granted to the president by the Constitution, and Lincoln was planning to take that action. In that month, Lincoln discussed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet. In it, he stated that "as a fit and necessary military measure, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves in the Confederate states will thenceforward, and forever, be free."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 364–365.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Privately, Lincoln concluded at this point that the war could not be won without freeing the slaves. However Confederate and anti-war propagandists had success spreading the theme that emancipation was a stumbling block to peace and reunification. Republican editor '
Begin Reference: Horace Greeley
End Reference: Horace Greeley
Text: ' of the highly influential ''New York Tribune'' fell for the ploy.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'McPherson (1992), p. 124.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' and Lincoln refuted it directly in a shrewd letter of August 22, 1862. The President said the primary goal of his actions as president (he used the first person pronoun and explicitly refers to his "official duty") was preserving the Union:'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Guelzo (2004), pp. 147–153.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Begin Template: quote
k: null
Text: 'My paramount object in this struggle is to save the Union, and is not either to save or to destroy slavery. If I could save the Union without freeing any slave I would do it, and if I could save it by freeing all the slaves I would do it; and if I could save it by freeing some and leaving others alone I would also do that. What I do about slavery, and the colored race, I do because I believe it helps to save the Union; and what I forbear, I forbear because I do not believe it would help to save the Union. . . . '
Text: '¶'
Text: ' I have here stated my purpose according to my view of official duty; and I intend no modification of my oft-expressed personal wish that all men everywhere could be free.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Roy P. Basler, ed. ''The collected works of Abraham Lincoln'' (Rutgers U.P., 1953) vol 5 p. 388'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' '
End Template: quote
Text: '

The Emancipation Proclamation, issued on September 22, 1862, and put into effect on January 1, 1863, declared free the slaves in 10 states not then under Union control, with exemptions specified for areas already under Union control in two states.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 364, 379.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Once the abolition of slavery in the rebel states became a military objective, as Union armies advanced south, more slaves were liberated until over three million of them in Confederate territory were freed. Lincoln's comment on the signing of the Proclamation was: "I never, in my life, felt more certain that I was doing right, than I do in signing this paper."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 407.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' For some time, Lincoln continued earlier plans to set up '
Begin Reference: Abraham Lincoln on slavery#Colonization
k: null
Text: 'colonies'
End Reference: Abraham Lincoln on slavery#Colonization
Text: ' for the newly freed slaves. He commented favorably on colonization in the Emancipation Proclamation, but all attempts at such a massive undertaking failed.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 408.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' A few days after Emancipation was announced, 13 Republican governors met at the '
Begin Reference: War Governors' Conference
End Reference: War Governors' Conference
Text: '; they supported the president's Proclamation, but suggested the removal of General George B. McClellan as commander of the Union Army.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Nevins (1960), pp. 2:239–240.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Using former slaves in the military was official government policy after the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation. At first, Lincoln was reluctant to fully implement this program, but by the spring of 1863, he was ready to initiate "a massive recruitment of Negro troops". In a letter to Andrew Johnson, the military governor of Tennessee, encouraging him to lead the way in raising black troops, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of 50,000 armed and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 430–431.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' By the end of 1863, at Lincoln's direction, General Lorenzo Thomas had recruited 20 regiments of blacks from the Mississippi Valley.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 431.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' '
Begin Reference: Frederick Douglass
End Reference: Frederick Douglass
Text: ' once observed of Lincoln: "In his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Douglass, pp. 259–260.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] Gettysburg Address
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: null
Text: 'Gettysburg Address'
End Template: Main
Text: '
With the great Union victory at the '
Begin Reference: Battle of Gettysburg
End Reference: Battle of Gettysburg
Text: ' in July 1863, and the defeat of the Copperheads in the Ohio election in the fall, Lincoln maintained a strong base of party support and was in a strong position to redefine the war effort, despite the '
Begin Reference: New York City draft riots
End Reference: New York City draft riots
Text: '. The stage was set for his address at the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 453–460.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Defying Lincoln's prediction that "the world will little note, nor long remember what we say here," the Address became the most quoted speech in American history.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Bulla']
Text: '

The Gettysburg Address was delivered at the dedication of the '
Begin Reference: Gettysburg National Cemetery
k: null
Text: 'Soldiers' National Cemetery'
End Reference: Gettysburg National Cemetery
Text: ' in Gettysburg, Pennsylvania, on the afternoon of Thursday, November 19, 1863. In 272 words, and three minutes, Lincoln asserted the nation was born not in 1789, but in 1776, "conceived in Liberty, and dedicated to the proposition that all men are created equal."   He defined the war as an effort dedicated to these principles of liberty and equality for all. The emancipation of slaves was now part of the national war effort.  He declared that the deaths of so many brave soldiers would not be in vain, that slavery would end as a result of the losses, and the future of democracy would be assured, that "government of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not perish from the earth." Lincoln concluded that the Civil War had a profound objective: a new birth of freedom in the nation.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 460–466.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Wills, pp. 20, 27, 105, 146.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] General Grant
Text: '
'
Begin Reference: File:The Peacemakers 1868.jpg
k: alt
Text: 'Painting of four men conferring in a ship's cabin, entitled "The Peacemakers".'
k: null
Text: 'thumb'
k: null
Text: '300px'
k: null
Text: 'President Lincoln (center right) with, from left, Generals Sherman, Grant and Admiral Porter – 1868 painting of events aboard the '''
Begin Reference: River Queen (steamboat)
k: null
Text: 'River Queen'
End Reference: River Queen (steamboat)
Text: ''' in March, 1865'
End Reference: File:The Peacemakers 1868.jpg
Text: '

Meade's failure to capture Lee's army as it retreated from Gettysburg, and the continued passivity of the Army of the Potomac, persuaded Lincoln that a change in command was needed. General '
Begin Reference: Ulysses S. Grant
End Reference: Ulysses S. Grant
Text: ''s victories at the '
Begin Reference: Battle of Shiloh
End Reference: Battle of Shiloh
Text: ' and in the '
Begin Reference: Vicksburg campaign
End Reference: Vicksburg campaign
Text: ' impressed Lincoln and made Grant a strong candidate to head the Union Army. Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln had said, "I can't spare this man. He fights."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Thomas (2008), p. 315.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' With Grant in command, Lincoln felt the Union Army could relentlessly pursue a series of coordinated offensives in multiple theaters, and have a top commander who agreed on the use of black troops.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Nevins (2000), (Vol. IV), pp. 6–17.'
Begin Template: full
End Template: full
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Nevertheless, Lincoln was concerned that Grant might be considering a candidacy for President in 1864, as McClellan was. Lincoln arranged for an intermediary to make inquiry into Grant's political intentions, and being assured that he had none, submitted to the Senate Grant's promotion to commander of the Union Army. He obtained Congress's consent to reinstate for Grant the rank of Lieutenant General, which no officer had held since George Washington.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 490–492.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Grant waged his bloody '
Begin Reference: Overland Campaign
End Reference: Overland Campaign
Text: ' in 1864. This is often characterized as a '
Begin Reference: attrition warfare
k: null
Text: 'war of attrition'
End Reference: attrition warfare
Text: ', given high Union losses at battles such as the '
Begin Reference: Battle of the Wilderness
End Reference: Battle of the Wilderness
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: Battle of Cold Harbor
k: null
Text: 'Cold Harbor'
End Reference: Battle of Cold Harbor
Text: '. Even though they had the advantage of fighting on the defensive, the Confederate forces had "almost as high a percentage of casualties as the Union forces".'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'McPherson (2009), p. 113.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' The high casualty figures of the Union alarmed the North; Grant had lost a third of his army, and Lincoln asked what Grant's plans were, to which the general replied, "I propose to fight it out on this line if it takes all summer."'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 501.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

The Confederacy lacked reinforcements, so Lee's army shrank with every battle, forcing it back to trenches outside Petersburg, Virginia, where Grant began a siege. Lincoln then made an extended visit to Grant's headquarters at City Point, Virginia. This allowed the president to confer in person with Grant and '
Begin Reference: William Tecumseh Sherman
End Reference: William Tecumseh Sherman
Text: ' about the hostilities, as Sherman coincidentally managed a hasty visit to Grant from his position in North Carolina.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'whitehousehistory']
Begin Template: cite web
k: url
Text: 'http://www.whitehousehistory.org/whha_about/whitehouse_collection/whitehouse_collection-art-06.html'
k: title
Text: 'The Peacemakers'
k: publisher
Text: 'The White House Historical Association'
k: archiveurl
Text: 'http://www.webcitation.org/62a8J9jOa'
k: archivedate
Text: 'October 20, 2011'
k: deadurl
End Template: cite web
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' Lincoln and the Republican party mobilized support for the draft throughout the North, and replaced his losses.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Thomas (2008), pp. 422–424.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Lincoln authorized Grant to target the Confederate infrastructure—such as plantations, railroads, and bridges—hoping to destroy the South's morale and weaken its economic ability to continue fighting. Grant's move to Petersburg resulted in the obstruction of three railroads between Richmond and the South. This strategy allowed Generals Sherman and '
Begin Reference: Philip Sheridan
End Reference: Philip Sheridan
Text: ' to destroy plantations and towns in Virginia's '
Begin Reference: Shenandoah Valley
End Reference: Shenandoah Valley
Text: '. The damage caused by '
Begin Reference: Sherman's March to the Sea
End Reference: Sherman's March to the Sea
Text: ' through Georgia in 1864 was limited to a '
Begin Template: convert
k: null
Text: '60'
k: null
Text: 'mi'
k: null
Text: 'km'
k: adj
Text: 'on'
End Template: convert
Text: ' swath, but neither Lincoln nor his commanders saw destruction as the main goal, but rather defeat of the Confederate armies. As Neely (2004) concludes, there was no effort to engage in "total war" against civilians, as in World War II.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Neely (2004), pp. 434–458.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

Confederate general '
Begin Reference: Jubal Anderson Early
End Reference: Jubal Anderson Early
Text: ' began a series of assaults in the North that threatened the Capital. During his '
Begin Reference: Battle of Fort Stevens
k: null
Text: 'raid on Washington, D.C.'
End Reference: Battle of Fort Stevens
Text: ' in 1864, Lincoln was watching the combat from an exposed position; Captain '
Begin Reference: Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr.
k: null
Text: 'Oliver Wendell Holmes'
End Reference: Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr.
Text: ' shouted at him, "Get down, you damn fool, before you get shot!"'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Thomas (2008), p. 434.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' After repeated calls on Grant to defend Washington, Sheridan was appointed and the threat from Early was dispatched.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 516–518.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

As Grant continued to wear down Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began. Confederate Vice President '
Begin Reference: Alexander H. Stephens
k: null
Text: 'Stephens'
End Reference: Alexander H. Stephens
Text: ' led a group to meet with Lincoln, Seward, and others at '
Begin Reference: Hampton Roads
End Reference: Hampton Roads
Text: '. Lincoln refused to allow any negotiation with the Confederacy as a coequal; his sole objective was an agreement to end the fighting and the meetings produced no results.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 565.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' On April 1, 1865, Grant successfully outflanked Lee's forces in the '
Begin Reference: Battle of Five Forks
End Reference: Battle of Five Forks
Text: ' and nearly encircled Petersburg, and the Confederate government evacuated Richmond. Days later, when that city fell, Lincoln visited the vanquished Confederate capital; as he walked through the city, white Southerners were stone-faced, but '
Begin Reference: freedmen
End Reference: freedmen
Text: ' greeted him as a hero. On April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at '
Begin Reference: Appomattox Court House
k: null
Text: 'Appomattox'
End Reference: Appomattox Court House
Text: ' and the war was effectively over.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), p. 589.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

'
Section [1] 1864 re-election
Text: '
'
Begin Template: Main
k: null
Text: 'Electoral history of Abraham Lincoln'
k: null
Text: 'United States presidential election, 1864'
End Template: Main
Text: '
Lincoln was a master politician, bringing together—and holding together—all the main factions of the Republican Party, and bringing in '
Begin Reference: War Democrats
End Reference: War Democrats
Text: ' such as '
Begin Reference: Edwin M. Stanton
End Reference: Edwin M. Stanton
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: Andrew Johnson
End Reference: Andrew Johnson
Text: ' as well.  Lincoln spent many hours a week talking to politicians from across the land and using his patronage powers—greatly expanded over peacetime—to hold the factions of his party together, build support for his own policies, and fend off efforts by Radicals to drop him from the 1864 ticket.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Fish, pp. 53–69.'
Close Tag: ref
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Tegeder, pp. 77–90.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: ' At its 1864 convention, the Republican Party selected '
Begin Reference: Andrew Johnson
End Reference: Andrew Johnson
Text: ', a War Democrat from the Southern state of Tennessee, as his running mate. To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the label of the new '
Begin Reference: National Union Party (United States)
k: null
Text: 'Union Party'
End Reference: National Union Party (United States)
Text: '.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Donald (1996), pp. 494–507.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '

When Grant's spring campaigns turned into bloody stalemates and Union casualties mounted, the lack of military success wore heavily on the President's re-election prospects, and many Republicans across the country feared that Lincoln would be defeated. Sharing this fear, Lincoln wrote and signed a pledge that, if he should lose the election, he would still defeat the Confederacy before turning over the White House:'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Grimsley, p. 80.'
Close Tag: ref
Text: '
'
Begin Template: quote
k: null
Text: 'This morning, as for some days past, it seems exceedingly probable that this Administration will not be re-elected. Then it will be my duty to so co-operate with the President elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterward.'
Open Tag: ref attributes: []
Text: 'Basler (1953), p. 514.'
Begin Template: full
End Template: full
Close Tag: ref
End Template: quote
Text: ' Lincoln did not show the pledge to his cabinet, but asked them to sign the sealed envelope.

'
